How it Works

Default Storage: Normally, attributes are stored in a __dict__ dictionary for each instance.
class Point:
    def __init__(self, x, y, z):
        self.x, self.y, self.z = x, y, z
p = Point(1, 2, 3)
print(p.__dict__)  # Output: {'x': 1, 'y': 2, 'z': 3}
Using __slots__: To restrict attributes, define a __slots__ tuple in the class.
class Point:
    __slots__ = ('x', 'y', 'z')
    def __init__(self, x, y, z):
        self.x, self.y, self.z = x, y, z

This prevents the addition of new attributes.
Eliminates the __dict__, thus saving memory.

